title: Cordray Theater, ca. 1892
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Theaters. Cordray theater. Third Avenue and Madison Street. Built 1890; demolished 1908. 1892. Toklas and Singerman's store 1889-1890. Madison Street Theater, 1890. Cordray Theater 1890-1894. Third Avenue Theater 1894-1908. Providence Hospital in background. Madison Street cable car at right. Caption: Madison St. Seattle 149 Boyd and Braas." Various names used for the same theatre at the University of Washington Digital Collection are: 'Theatre, northeast corner of 3rd Ave. and Madison St., Seattle. Theatre is advertising 'The Taylor Co.' and 'Queen of the Highway'. Known earlier as the Madison St. Theatre, then Cordray's Theatre, it was originally built as a store. The Lincoln Hotel is in the background at 4th Ave. and Madison St.'  Index card verifies date as 1892.

title: Native Americans on waterfront in Belltown, ca. 1882
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Waterfronts. 1882-1886. Canoe and Indians. Foot of Vine Street, Cedar Street and Broad Street. A common scene in 1882, '83,'84, '85, '86 at the West end of Vine, Cedar, Broad Streets, Seattle. The canoes were those of Indians on their way from the North to the hop fields of White and Puyallup Valleys. This part of the city front has since been covered by four lines of railroad, wharves, warehouses, shops, streets, etc."
